01:25:58.220 --> 01:26:01.030
So if we have a tool like
that, you have a model.

01:26:01.030 --> 01:26:04.500
You have your input instruments,
and you have some regularizing

01:26:04.500 --> 01:26:06.150
terms of it could
be smoothness, it

01:26:06.150 --> 01:26:09.910
could be a PCA, it could be
combination of PCA, right?

01:26:09.910 --> 01:26:13.200
But then that
additional information

01:26:13.200 --> 01:26:17.410
allows you to find
anomalies in the market.

01:26:17.410 --> 01:26:19.250
Once you find those
anomalies, you

01:26:19.250 --> 01:26:22.670
can take advantage of them--
provided that your model is

01:26:22.670 --> 01:26:24.480
robust enough.

01:26:24.480 --> 01:26:27.970
And if you are saying, well,
I am kind of doing well,

01:26:27.970 --> 01:26:31.350
and I'm calibrate well with
just some smoothness assumption

01:26:31.350 --> 01:26:33.410
about smoothness of
the forward rates,

01:26:33.410 --> 01:26:35.850
there is nothing more
fundamental than this.

01:26:35.850 --> 01:26:41.980
So if your model is based
on fundamental principle,

01:26:41.980 --> 01:26:44.990
you can expect that it will
be more stable in the future,

01:26:44.990 --> 01:26:45.820
rather than PCA.

01:26:45.820 --> 01:26:47.795
Because for PCA, you
just kind of say,

01:26:47.795 --> 01:26:49.590
OK, I took the time interval.

01:26:49.590 --> 01:26:55.090
I kind of did my regression
analysis, whatever.

01:26:55.090 --> 01:26:57.800
But that doesn't mean that
the market will continue

01:26:57.800 --> 01:26:59.400
to do the same in the future.

