01:27:30.150 --> 01:27:33.730
And some firms do that.

01:27:33.730 --> 01:27:36.190
The problem is
that with swaps, we

01:27:36.190 --> 01:27:42.010
kind of have those swaps
today, they kind of

01:27:42.010 --> 01:27:44.560
roll every day, OK?

01:27:44.560 --> 01:27:48.164
They like, the swap today
starts today, swap tomorrow

01:27:48.164 --> 01:27:49.580
starts tomorrow,
things like that.

01:27:49.580 --> 01:27:51.550
But bonds do not.

01:27:51.550 --> 01:27:56.750
OK so they basically, there
is like on-the-run bond, which

01:27:56.750 --> 01:28:00.510
is the most liquid one, which
once the new ten-year bond is

01:28:00.510 --> 01:28:04.060
issued, then that bond
becomes off-the-run.

01:28:04.060 --> 01:28:05.790
It's still traded,
but then everyone

01:28:05.790 --> 01:28:07.800
switches to on-the-run.

01:28:07.800 --> 01:28:13.300
So you don't have a nice
continuous spectrum of bonds.

01:28:13.300 --> 01:28:15.670
You have kind of concentrations
between on-the-runs

01:28:15.670 --> 01:28:17.400
and off-the-runs.

01:28:17.400 --> 01:28:21.960
And if you want to draw
the curve for all of them,

01:28:21.960 --> 01:28:24.990
you typically cannot
do the perfect fit.

01:28:24.990 --> 01:28:29.160
You kind of need to
do the least squares.

01:28:29.160 --> 01:28:33.310
So it's just more convenient
to do it in the swap.

01:28:33.310 --> 01:28:38.730
But once we build the swap
curve, swap trader typically--

01:28:38.730 --> 01:28:41.170
I should say always
use bonds for hedging,

01:28:41.170 --> 01:28:44.080
just because bonds
are much more liquid.

01:28:44.080 --> 01:28:48.220
Then we project bonds
to the swap curve

01:28:48.220 --> 01:28:51.240
rather than swaps to the bond
curve, which is hard to build.

01:28:52.206 --> 01:28:53.977
AUDIENCE: So in
this case, when they

01:28:53.977 --> 01:28:57.036
switch from on-the-run,
off-the-run, [INAUDIBLE]?

01:29:01.069 --> 01:29:01.860
IVAN MASYUKOV: Yes.

01:29:01.860 --> 01:29:05.700
So your curve won't be stable,
just because those roll

01:29:05.700 --> 01:29:09.690
effects-- we call
those "roll effects"--

01:29:09.690 --> 01:29:12.580
which means that there is
something substantial changes

01:29:12.580 --> 01:29:13.170
on the market.

01:29:13.170 --> 01:29:14.900
And there may be
such a big demand

01:29:14.900 --> 01:29:21.650
for this new bond on the market,
that will make your curve, that

01:29:21.650 --> 01:29:23.700
won't look nice.

01:29:23.700 --> 01:29:27.410
So there are also traders
that just trade bonds.

01:29:27.410 --> 01:29:32.470
And those typically
don't have curves.

01:29:32.470 --> 01:29:36.638
They rely on some PCA
models, or some other things.

